# Git safety

## Never run `git stash` without explicit permission

Do **not** run `git stash`, `git stash push`, `git stash pop`, `git stash apply`, or `git stash drop` unless the user explicitly asks in the current message.

Stashing reverts tracked files to `HEAD`. In this repo, most feature work is uncommitted on top of an old `first commit`; stashing silently restores ancient code and breaks the tree.

## If you need a clean tree for comparison

Ask the user first. Safer alternatives:

- `git diff` / `git status` (read-only)
- a second clone or `git worktree` (with user approval)
- copy changed files aside (with user approval)

## Other destructive git commands

Same rule: no `git reset --hard`, `git checkout -- .`, `git clean -fd`, or `git restore` on broad paths unless the user explicitly requests it.

## Commits

Only commit when the user asks (see user commit rules). After large recoveries, suggest committing so `HEAD` is not left on stale baseline — do not commit unprompted.
